<DOC><DOCNO> AP881230-0182 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 2340EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-EthnicAlbanians     12-30 0199</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Ethnic Albanians,0201</SECOND><HEAD>Eight Sentenced for Hostile Activity</HEAD><DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A district court in southernYugoslavia on Friday sentenced eight ethnic Albanians to prisonterms ranging from four to 11 years for ``hostile activity,'' theofficial Tanjug news agency reported.   It said the court found them guilty of organizing a demonstrationby hundreds of ethnic Albanian schoolchildren last October in theMacedonian town of Gostivar to protest a decision by educationauthorities to limit instruction in the Albanian language.   Ajredin Kaza, 32, the alleged head of the group, drew 11 years inprison; Nazif Zinani, 29, and Zulufchli Dalipi, 29, each receivedeight years; Imrli Bektesiju, 19, was sentenced to six years andfour unidentified minors were meted prison terms ranging from fourto six years, Tanjug said.   The southern republic of Macedonia has been the scene ofincreasing ethnic strife between the majority Slav population and arapidly growing minority of ethnic Albanians, who have been movingsouth from troubled Kosovo province.   Hundreds of ethnic Albanians have been sentenced to long jailterms in Kosovo since riots there in 1981, when some ethnicAlbanians demanded greater autonomy for the province and its ethnicAlbanian population.</TEXT></DOC>